ut 1127–about 1170","1127–1170":"1127–1170","1145–Female":"1145–Deceased","1165–1197":"1165–1197","1037–1127":"1037–1127","1050–Female":"1050–Deceased","about 1170":"about 1170","1127":"1127","WFT Est. 1142-1197":"from about 1142 to 1197","1037":"1037","about 1127":"about 1127","1145":"1145","1165":"1165","1197":"1197","about 1165":"about 1165","1050":"1050","1170":"1170","Wales":"Wales","Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Kidwelly","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Devon, and Glamorgan in Scotland): nickname from Middle English <i>kid</i> ‘kid, young goat’ + <i>wild</i> ‘wild’, i.e. ‘frisky as a kid’."],"variants":[{"name":"Keadle","meanings":["English: variant of <b>Kiddle</b> (see   Kidwell  )."]}]},{"name":"Ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]},{"name":"Lord","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of   Lorraine   or variant spelling of   Laurie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Lorraine","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, in origin denoting a migrant from the province of <i>Lorraine</i> in eastern France. This derives its name from Latin <i>Lotharingia</i> ‘territory of the people of <i>Lothar</i>’. The latter is a Germanic personal name derived from <i>hlud</i> ‘fame’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. <i>Lorraine</i> began to be used as a girl's name in Scotland in the 19th century, and for a time in the second half of the 20th century enjoyed great popularity, which has since waned."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Oswald   or any of the various other names beginning with <i>Os-</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lloarch Ap Kynhathwye Lord of Kidwelly was born about 1127, in Wales, his father, Lord Kyhathwye ap Gurwared, was 91 and his mother, Lady Kyhathwye ap Gurwared, was 79. He married Lloarch ap Klow Kidwelly in 1165, in Carmarthenshire, Wales. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died about 1170, in his hometown, at the age of 45."},"et":{"about 1127–about 1170":"umbes 1127–umbes 1170","1127–1170":"1127–1170","1145–Female":"1145–Surnud","1165–1197":"1165–1197","1037–1127":"1037–1127","1050–Female":"1050–Surnud","about 1170":"umbes 1170","1127":"1127","WFT Est. 1142-1197":"umbes 1142 kuni 1197","1037":"1037","about 1127":"umbes 1127","1145":"1145","1165":"1165","1197":"1197","about 1165":"umbes 1165","1050":"1050","1170":"1170","Wales":"Wales","Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales"},"fi":{"about 1127–about 1170":"noin 1127–noin 1170","1127–1170":"1127–1170","1145–Female":"1145–Kuollut","1165–1197":"1165–1197","1037–1127":"1037–1127","1050–Female":"1050–Kuollut","about 1170":"noin 1170","1127":"1127","WFT Est. 1142-1197":"vuodesta noin 1142 vuoteen 1197","1037":"1037","about 1127":"noin 1127","1145":"1145","1165":"1165","1197":"1197","about 1165":"noin 1165","1050":"1050","1170":"1170","Wales":"Wales","Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales"},"fr":{"about 1127–about 1170":"environ 1127–environ 1170","1127–1170":"1127–1170","1145–Female":"1145–Décédée","1165–1197":"1165–1197","1037–1127":"1037–1127","1050–Female":"1050–Décédée","about 1170":"environ 1170","1127":"1127","WFT Est. 1142-1197":"du environ 1142 au 1197","1037":"1037","about 1127":"environ 1127","1145":"1145","1165":"1165","1197":"1197","about 1165":"environ 1165","1050":"1050","1170":"1170","Wales":"Galles","Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Galles","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Lloarch Ap Kynhathwye Lord of Kidwelly est né environ 1127, à Galles, son père, Lord Kyhathwye ap Gurwared, avait 91 ans et sa mère, Lady Kyhathwye ap Gurwared, avait 79 ans. Il a épousé Lloarch ap Klow Kidwelly en 1165, à Carmarthenshire, Galles. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils. Il est décédé environ 1170, dans sa ville natale, à l’â